'''Ait-Awari''' are a [[Tuareg people|Tuareg]] tribe<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9AsNAQAAMAAJ&q=ait-awari&dq=ait-awari&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimsb6bhpjUAhVJKsAKHbMuAi8Q6AEIWDAJ|title=L'Homme: revue française d'anthropologie|last=|first=|date=1990|publisher=Mouton|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=42|language=fr}}</ref> probably originating from northern [[berber mythology|Berber]] peoples who emigrated southwards centuries ago. Their language, called [[Tin Sert language|Tin Sert]] or Tetserret, may indicate that they came from the gulf of [[Sirte]] in [[Libya]].

Today the Ait-Awari community is estimated in a few thousands, they live mainly in the ''Akabinu'' ([[Akoubounou]]) commune in [[Niger]].

