{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Iranians in Spain |rels = [[Shia Islam]], Zoroastrianism, Judaism, [[Atheism]] |population = 12,344 (2011)<ref>{{harvnb|INE|2009}}</ref> <!-- Do not insert further entries to the infobox without reliable sources --> }}
'''Iranians in Spain''' do not form a very large population, but they have a history going back for over a millennium.<ref>{{harvnb|López García|Planet Contreras|2002|p=162}}</ref><ref name="Kenesson">{{harvnb|Kenesson|1992|pp=107–108}}</ref> They are a part of the [[Iranian diaspora]].
==Migration history== [[Muhammad ibn Zakariya ar-Razi|Razi]] wrote in the 10th century that some Iranians had already settled in Spain, and [[Ibn Battuta]] later claimed the Iranians of Spain preferred to live in [[Granada]] because of its similarity to their homeland.<ref name="Kenesson" /> However, the impetus for modern Iranian immigration to Spain came largely from the 1979 [[Iranian Revolution]], as a result of which some Iranians went to Spain as political refugees.<ref>{{harvnb|Jamshid|1982}}</ref><ref name="LopezGarcia">{{harvnb|López García|Planet Contreras|2002|p=164}}</ref>
==Demography== A 1992 survey found that 31.7% worked in administrative jobs, 18.2% were professionals or technicians, 25.7% worked in trade, and another 11% worked in agriculture. The vast majority were 25-54 years of age, and only one-fifth were women.<ref>{{harvnb|López García|Planet Contreras|2002|p=165}}</ref> This is actually a relatively large proportion of women compared to other [[Islam in Spain|Muslim migrant communities in Spain]], which may be attributed to the fact that most Iranians in Spain are political, rather than economic migrants.<ref name="LopezGarcia" />
==Notable people== *[[Don Juan of Persia]], 17th century notable *[[Ahdieh]], popular singer *[[Mehrdad Khonsari]], former diplomat, politician and writer *[[Manouchehr Farhangi]], entrepreneur, Zoroastrian thinker, founder of [[International College Spain]]
