{{For|the Australian soprano|Jennifer McGregor (soprano)}} '''Jennifer McGregor''' is an American curator and arts planner. Based in New York, she is the Director of Arts and senior [[curator]] at [[Wave Hill]], a public garden and cultural center in the Bronx, New York City.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.wavehill.org/about/board-staff/ | title = Board & Staff | publisher = Wave Hill, New York Public Garden and Cultural Center | access-date = 2016-03-01 }}</ref> There she curates exhibitions and oversees performances that relate to nature, culture and site.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://artistcareerguide.com/interviews/jennifer-mcgregor | title = Reality Check Interview with Jennifer McGregor | website = artistcareerguide.com | access-date = 2016-03-01 }}</ref> Recent projects include an immersive outdoor installation by [[Chris Doyle (artist)|Chris Doyle]], ''The Lightening – A Project for Wave Hill's Aquatic Garden''<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/14/nyregion/outdoor-installation-at-wave-hill-celebrates-its-history-of-art-shows.html | title = Wave Hill Puts Spotlight on Art to Celebrate Its Gardens and Lure Visitors | last = Hu | first = Winnie | date = 2015-05-13 | newspaper = The New York Times | issn = 0362-4331 | access-date = 2016-03-01 }}</ref> and the exhibition ''Field Notes'' featuring projects by Matthew Friday, David McQueen and [[Michelle Stuart]].<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://arts.vcu.edu/sculpture/field-notes/ | title = Field Notes | website = VCU Sculpture + Extended Media | access-date = 2016-03-01 }}</ref> McGregor started working in the field as the first director of the New York City's [[Percent for Art]] Program between 1983 and 1990.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.nyc.gov/html/dcla/html/panyc/faq.shtml#history | title = FAQ – NYC Department of Cultural Affairs | website = www.nyc.gov | access-date = 2016-03-01 }}</ref> She has served as a consultant on many [[public art]] and policy projects including a public art plan for the [[Rose Fitzgerald Kennedy Greenway]] in Boston, Massachusetts, in 2012; a public art plan for [[Laramie, Wyoming]], in 2015,<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.laramiepublicart.org | title = Laramie Public Art || access-date = 2016-03-01 }}</ref> and project management for New York City's [[American Airlines Flight 587|Flight 587]] Memorial in 2006; managed the commissioned artwork by [[Daniel Hauben]] for the New Instructional Building at the [[Bronx Community College]], and more.
