{{Infobox language |name=Mampruli |nativename=Mamprusi |states=[[Ghana]] |ethnicity=[[Mamprusi people]] |speakers=230,000 |date=2004 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Gur languages|Gur]] |fam4=Northern |fam5=[[Oti–Volta languages|Oti–Volta]] |fam6=Western-Oti/Volta |fam7=Southeastern |iso3=maw |glotto=mamp1244 |glottorefname=Mampruli }} {{infobox ethnonym||Mamprusi|Mampruli (Ŋmampulli?)|Mamprugu}}
'''Mamprusi''' (autonym '''''Mampruli''','' also ''Mampelle, Ŋmampulli)'' is a [[Gur language]] spoken in northern [[Ghana]] by the [[Mamprusi]] people. It is partially [[mutually intelligible]] with [[Dagbani language|Dagbani]]. The Mamprusi language is spoken in a broad belt across the northern parts of the [[Northern Region (Ghana)|Northern Region]] of Ghana, stretching west to east from Yizeesi to [[Nakpanduri]] and centred on the towns of [[Gambaga]]/[[Nalerigu]] and [[Walewale]]. In Mamprusi, one speaker is a ''Ŋmampuriga'', many (plural) are ''Ŋmampurisi'' and the land of the Mamprusi is ''Ŋmampurigu''.
The language belongs to the Gur family which is part of the [[Niger–Congo language family]], which covers most of [[Sub-Saharan Africa]] (Bendor-Samuel 1989). Within Gur it belongs to the Western [[Oti–Volta]] subgroup, and particularly its southeastern cluster of six to eight languages ([[Tony Naden|Naden]] 1988, 1989). Closely related and very similar languages spoken nearby are Dagbani, Nanun, [[Kamara language|Kamara]] and [[Hanga language|Hanga]] in the Northern Region, and [[Kusaal language|Kusaal]], [[Nabit language|Nabit]] and [[Talni language|Talni]] in the [[Upper East Region]]. Not quite so closely related are [[Farefare language|Farefare]], [[Wali language (Gur)|Waali]], [[Dagaari language|Dagaari]], [[Birifor language|Birifor]] and [[Safaliba language|Safalaba]] in the Upper East and [[Upper West Region|Upper West Regions]] and southwest of the Northern Region.
Comparatively little linguistic material on the language has been published; there is a brief sketch as an illustration of this subgroup of languages in Naden 1988.<ref>{{cite book|last=Tony|first=[[Tony Naden|Naden]]|title=Gur Languages|publisher=Kegan Paul International ''for'' I.A.I. /W.A.L.S.|location=London|pages=12–49}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Dakubu|first=Mary Esther Kropp [ed.]|title=The Languages of Ghana|date=1988|publisher=Kegan Paul International ''for'' I.A.I. /W.A.L.S|location=London}}</ref> A collection of Mampruli proverbs has been published by R.P. Xavier Plissart,<ref>{{cite book|last=Plissart|first=Xavier|title=Mampruli Proverbs|date=1983|publisher=Musée Royale de l'Afrique|location=Tervuren}}</ref> and a translation of the New Testament is in print,<ref>{{cite book|last=n/a|first=n/a|title=Naawunni Kunni Palli (''God's New Volume'')|date=2001|publisher=GILLBT|location=Tamale}}</ref> a sample of which can be read and heard online.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matiu 1|url=http://www.bible.is/MAWWBT/Matt/1}}</ref> There are also beginning Mampruli lessons in which the spoken language can be heard.<ref>{{cite web|title=Red Mountain Mampruli Project|url=http://www.redmountainwriting.com/philanthropy/the_mampruli_project}}</ref>
==Dialects==
There is comparatively little dialect variation. The western (Walewale to the [[White Volta]]) and Far Western (west of the White Volta, area known by those to the east as "Overseas") have some variant pronunciation standards. The far Eastern dialect known as Durili is most notable for pronouncing ''[r]'' and ''[l]'' where the rest of Mampruli pronounces ''[l]'' and ''[r]'' respectively, and for some characteristic intonation patterns.
==Phonology==
