{{Infobox language family |name=Ob-Ugric |acceptance=controversial |region=Central [[Russia]] |familycolor=Uralic |fam2=[[Ugric languages|Ugric]] ? |child1=[[Khanty language|Khanty (Ostyak)]] |child2=[[Mansi language|Mansi (Vogul)]] |glotto=none |map=Lenguas obiungrias.png |mapcaption=The Ob-Ugric languages }}
The '''Ob-Ugric languages''' are a hypothetical{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} branch of the [[Uralic languages]], specifically referring to the [[Khanty language|Khanty]] (Ostyak) and [[Mansi language|Mansi]] (Vogul) languages. Both are split in numerous and highly divergent dialects. They, along with [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], comprise the [[Ugric languages|Ugric]] branch of the [[Uralic languages]].
The languages are spoken in the region between the [[Urals]] and the [[Ob River]] and the [[Irtysh]] in central [[Russia]]. The forests and forest steppes of the southern Urals are thought to be the original homeland of the Ugric branch. Beginning some 500 years ago the arrival of the Russians pushed the speakers eastward to the Ob and Irtysh. Some Mansi speakers remained west of the Urals until as late as the early 20th century. [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] split off during the 11th century BC.<ref>{{cite book | author = Hajdú, Péter | year = 1981 | title = Az uráli nyelvészet alapkérdései | publisher = Tankönyvkiadó, Budapest | isbn = 963-17-4219-9 | authorlink = Péter Hajdú }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author = Jászó, Anna | year = 1994 | title = A magyar nyelv könyve | publisher = Trezor Kiadó, Budapest | isbn = 963-7685-42-1}}</ref> [[File:Khanty Mansi dialects.svg|thumbnail|300px|Khanty (reddish and greenish) and Mansi (bluish) dialects]] The status of the Ob-Ugric languages as a close [[Sprachbund|areal]] grouping is clear, with adjacent varieties regularly sharing isoglosses and having loaned vocabulary back and forth (as well as from common external sources, e.g. from eastern dialects of [[Komi language|Komi]] into northern dialects of Mansi and Khanty). This effect is particularly clear between the more eastern and northern varieties of Mansi, and the more western varieties of Khanty. Modern-day Northern Mansi and Northern Khanty continue to affect each other's evolution. Some areal similarities are also shared with their eastern Samoyedic relatives, in particular between Khanty and [[Selkup language|Selkup]], but also [[Forest Nenets language|Forest Nenets]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=Eugene|last=Helimski|title=Areal groupings (Sprachbünde) within and across the borders of the Uralic language family: A survey|year=2003|journal=Nyelvtudományi Közlemények|ISSN=0029-6791|url=http://www.nytud.hu/nyk/100/helimski.pdf|accessdate=2014-10-31|pp=160–163}}</ref> The relationship to Hungarian is looser: in their current state, the Ob-Ugric languages are radically different from Hungarian in phonology, syntax, and vocabulary.
Typological features distinguishing the Ob-Ugric languages include:<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | first = Bela | last = Kálmán | year = 1988 | editor-first = Denis| editor-last= Sinor| title = The History of the Ob-Ugric Languages | encyclopedia = The Uralic Languages | publisher = Brill | location = Leiden}}</ref> * The lack of a systematic [[Voice (phonetics)|voicing]] contrast. {{IPA|/ɣ/}}, however, is a frequent consonant word-medially. * Retention of Proto-Uralic word-initial *w as /w/. (Also a feature of [[Nenets languages|Nenets]].) * [[Vowel harmony]] is found in the most archaic varieties, southern Mansi and eastern Khanty. * [[Ablaut]] of vowels, particularly in eastern Khanty * In the northern dialects: a change *k → /x/ before [[back vowel]]s. (A similar change also occurred in Hungarian.) * Retention of [[subject–object–verb]] (SOV) word order * Retention of [[Dual (grammatical number)|dual number]] * Partial or full replacement of the original [[Grammatical person|2nd person]] pronominal and suffixal elements; marked by the consonant /t/ in most Uralic languages but for the most part /n/ in Ob-Ugric. * A smaller [[grammatical case|case]] system than in other Uralic languages, including a lack of the [[genitive case]].
The Ob-Ugric languages have also been strongly influenced by nearby [[Turkic languages]], especially [[Tatar language|Tatar]].<ref>{{cite book | author = Greller, Wolfgang | date = 2000-04-01 | title = Encyclopedia of the Languages of Europe | publisher = Blackwell Publishing | isbn = 0-631-22039-9 | page = 478}}</ref>
Mansi has about 1,000 speakers while Khanty has about 10,000 speakers, all within Russia. Until 1930, these languages had no written or literary traditions, but since 1937 have used a modified [[Cyrillic alphabets|Cyrillic alphabet]]. However, no significant texts have been created in these languages and they have few official usages.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9056621 | title = Ob-Ugric languages | accessdate = 2006-06-22 | publisher = Encyclopædia Britannica}}</ref>
The existence of a common Ob-Ugric period after the separation from Hungarian and the rest of Uralic is not universally accepted: some linguists treat all common features of Mansi and Khanty as either later convergence under mutual influence, or retentions from the common Ugric and earlier periods.
